# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: proof-of-stake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] When launched in 2017, it was the largest cryptocurrency to use a proof of stake blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] A number of independent entities collaborate on the project, including the Cardano Foundation based in Zug, Switzerland, and led by its chief executive officer Frederik Gregaard.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] After leaving Ethereum in 2014, Charles Hoskinson and Jeremy Wood set out their plans for establishing Cardano in 2015.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Hoskinson had left Ethereum after a dispute with another co-founder, Vitalik Buterin; Hoskinson wanted to accept venture capital and create a company, while Buterin wanted to keep it as a nonprofit organization.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Wood and Hoskinson co-founded the business IOHK to develop blockchains for use by corporations, governments, and education institutions.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Cardano was initially released to the public in 2017.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] That year, IOHK partnered with the University of Edinburgh to launch the Blockchain Technology Laboratory.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The lab had six post-doctoral and professorial positions with up to 35 jobs created in total, and was led by Aggelos Kiayias, developer of the Ouroboros protocol.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Cardano reached a market cap of $77 billion in May 2021, which was the fourth highest for a cryptocurrency at that time.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Advertising agency MBLM ranked Cardano 26th for brand intimacy out of 600 brands in August 2022, in between Ford and Nestlé and the highest rank for a cryptocurrency.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Citing an MBLM partner, advertising industry magazine *Ad Age* said Cardano's high ranking "can likely be chalked up to the gambling element of crypto".
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The platform is named after Italian mathematician Gerolamo Cardano, while the cryptocurrency itself is named after the English mathematician Ada Lovelace.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The Ada sub-unit is the Lovelace; one Ada = 1,000,000 Lovelaces.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Atypically, Cardano does not have a foundational white paper.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Instead, it uses design principles intended to overcome issues—such as scalability, interoperability, and a lack of regulatory compliance—faced by earlier cryptocurrencies.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Cardano claims that it overcomes problems found in other cryptocurrencies, mainly that Bitcoin is too slow and inflexible and that Ethereum is not safe or scalable.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Like Bitcoin, Cardano uses a UTXO ledger model, though it is an extended version (EUTXO) to facilitate smart contracts and scripting languages.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Cardano uses a proof-of-stake (PoS) protocol named Ouroboros; this was in contrast to Bitcoin and Ethereum, which used proof-of-work protocols (though the latter switched over in 2022).
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Proof-of-stake blockchains use far less energy than proof-of-work chains.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] This is achieved by eliminating the computing resources that a proof-of-work algorithm requires.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] In February 2021, Hoskinson estimated the Cardano network used 6 GWh annually, less than 0.01% of the 110.53 TWh used by the Bitcoin network as calculated by researchers at the University of Cambridge.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Within the Cardano platform, the settlement layer keeps track of transactions.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The second layer is the computation layer and is designed to be similar to Ethereum, enabling smart contracts and applications to run on the platform.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Like other cryptocurrencies, Ada (ADA) can be stored on a digital wallet.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Cardano's native digital wallet is named "Daedalus".
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The Daedalus wallet downloads a full copy of the entire transaction history of the Cardano blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Wallet users face the risk of losing access to funds if the wallet's seed phrase is lost or stolen.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Development phases of Cardano are named after notable figures in poetry and computer science: Byron, Shelley, Goguen, Basho, and Voltaire.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The first three stages implemented a basic blockchain, and then implemented decentralisation and smart contracts.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The Basho era focuses on scaling the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The Voltaire release adds a treasury model.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Once part of Cardano's Voltaire phase, CIP-1694 was implemented through the Chang upgrade and subsequent Plomin hard fork in 2024 establishing "on-chain" governance.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] This transition enabled ADA token holders to create, vote on and implement proposals through a decentralized decision-making process, marking IOHK's successful transfer of network development control to the community.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] As with other proof-of-stake cryptocurrencies, Cardano offers "staking", which allows token holders to set-aside (delegate) tokens to potentially "validate" transactions on the same blockchain *(Figure 1)*.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The quantity of tokens staked corresponds with the likelihood of being chosen to validate a transaction, and thus be rewarded by the algorithm with more of the same token.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Through various wallet implementations, users can participate in "staking pools" with other token holders.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] These staked tokens have a dual purpose, both securing the network through validation and enabling participation in the governance system.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Since 2021, Frederik Gregaard has been the CEO of the Cardano Foundation.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Cardano implemented decentralized finance (DeFi) services on September 12, 2021, including an upgrade to enable smart contracts and the ability to build decentralized applications (DApps).
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Also included is Plutus, a smart contract language written in Haskell, and Marlowe, a domain-specific language designed by Simon Thompson for non-programmers in the financial sector.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] In November 2023 Cardano began introducing sidechains, referred to by the project as "partner chains".
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Sidechains are intended to perform off-chain computations, known as smart contracts, while using the Cardano network for settlement.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The first example of such a chain, named "Midnight", will make use of the Polkadot framework in combination with Cardano.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Cardano also enables creating non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Snoop Dogg released several thousand NFTs in a project named "Baked Nation" for the Cardano chain in April 2022.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] In 2023 a digital artist from the UK sold 7,200 individual works of humanoid deer for almost £500,000 on Cardano.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Without any admission of wrongdoing, Kraken agreed to pay a fine of $30 million and halt its staking program in response.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Among the allegations was that Cardano was a security and so the cryptocurrency exchange was trading illegally in the US.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] IOG responded that the filing was inaccurate and that Ada was not a security.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Robinhood Markets said it would remove Cardano and two other proof of stake coins from its platform.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The Ada price fell from $0.38 to $0.26 in a day on the FT Wilshire index.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] Both the *Wall Street Journal* and *The Times* linked a fall in the price of Cardano – 19 per cent in June – and a slide for other major coins to the SEC's actions.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] In late November, Robinhood re-enabled trading in Ada.
[src:proof-of-stake/cardano-blockchain-platform] The price was $1.09 at the end of the month.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Proof-of-stake (PoS) underlies Ethereum's consensus mechanism.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Ethereum switched on its proof-of-stake mechanism in 2022 because it is more secure, less energy-intensive, and better for implementing new scaling solutions compared to the previous proof-of-work architecture.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] To better understand this page, we recommend you first read up on consensus mechanisms.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Proof-of-stake is a way to prove that validators have put something of value into the network that can be destroyed if they act dishonestly.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] In Ethereum's proof-of-stake, validators explicitly stake capital in the form of ETH into a smart contract on Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The validator is then responsible for checking that new blocks propagated over the network are valid and occasionally creating and propagating new blocks themselves.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] If they try to defraud the network (for example by proposing multiple blocks when they ought to send one or sending conflicting attestations), some or all of their staked ETH can be destroyed.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] To participate as a validator, a user must deposit 32 ETH into the deposit contract and run three separate pieces of software: an execution client, a consensus client, and a validator client.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] On depositing their ETH, the user joins an activation queue that limits the rate of new validators joining the network.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Once activated, validators receive new blocks from peers on the Ethereum network.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The transactions delivered in the block are re-executed to check that the proposed changes to Ethereum's state are valid, and the block signature is checked.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The validator then sends a vote (called an attestation) in favor of that block across the network.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Whereas under proof-of-work, the timing of blocks is determined by the mining difficulty, in proof-of-stake, the tempo is fixed.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Time in proof-of-stake Ethereum is divided into slots (12 seconds) and epochs (32 slots).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] One validator is randomly selected to be a block proposer in every slot.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This validator is responsible for creating a new block and sending it out to other nodes on the network.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Also in every slot, a committee of validators is randomly chosen, whose votes are used to determine the validity of the block being proposed.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Dividing the validator set up into committees is important for keeping the network load manageable.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Committees divide up the validator set so that every active validator attests in every epoch, but not in every slot.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The following provides an end-to-end explanation of how a transaction gets executed in Ethereum proof-of-stake.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The transaction is submitted to an Ethereum execution client which verifies its validity.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This means ensuring that the sender has enough ETH to fulfill the transaction and they have signed it with the correct key.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] If the transaction is valid, the execution client adds it to its local mempool (list of pending transactions) and also broadcasts it to other nodes over the execution layer gossip network.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] When other nodes hear about the transaction they add it to their local mempool too.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Advanced users might refrain from broadcasting their transaction and instead forward it to specialized block builders such as Flashbots Auction (opens in a new tab).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This allows them to organize the transactions in upcoming blocks for maximum profit (MEV).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] One of the validator nodes on the network is the block proposer for the current slot, having previously been selected pseudo-randomly using RANDAO.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This node is responsible for building and broadcasting the next block to be added to the Ethereum blockchain and updating the global state.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The node is made up of three parts: an execution client, a consensus client and a validator client.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The execution client bundles transactions from the local mempool into an "execution payload" and executes them locally to generate a state change.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This information is passed to the consensus client where the execution payload is wrapped as part of a "beacon block" that also contains information about rewards, penalties, slashings, attestations etc. that enable the network to agree on the sequence of blocks at the head of the chain.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The communication between the execution and consensus clients is described in more detail in Connecting the Consensus and Execution Clients.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Other nodes receive the new beacon block on the consensus layer gossip network.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] They pass it to their execution client where the transactions are re-executed locally to ensure the proposed state change is valid.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The validator client then attests that the block is valid and is the logical next block in their view of the chain (meaning it builds on the chain with the greatest weight of attestations as defined in the fork choice rules).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The block is added to the local database in each node that attests to it.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The transaction can be considered "finalized" if it has become part of a chain with a "supermajority link" between two checkpoints.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Checkpoints occur at the start of each epoch and they exist to account for the fact that only a subset of active validators attest in each slot, but all active validators attest across each epoch.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Therefore, it is only between epochs that a 'supermajority link' can be demonstrated (this is where 66% of the total staked ETH on the network agrees on two checkpoints).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] More detail on finality can be found below.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] A transaction has "finality" in distributed networks when it is part of a block that can't change without a large amount of ETH getting burned.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] On proof-of-stake Ethereum, this is managed using "checkpoint" blocks.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The first block in each epoch is a checkpoint.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Validators vote for pairs of checkpoints that it considers to be valid.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] If a pair of checkpoints attracts votes representing at least two-thirds of the total staked ETH, the checkpoints are upgraded.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The more recent of the two (target) becomes "justified".
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The earlier of the two is already justified because it was the "target" in the previous epoch.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This process of upgrading the checkpoints is handled by **Casper the Friendly Finality Gadget (Casper-FFG) (opens in a new tab)**.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Casper-FFG is a block finality tool for consensus.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Once a block is finalized, it cannot be reverted or changed without a majority slashing of stakers, making it economically inviable.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] To revert a finalized block, an attacker would commit to losing at least one-third of the total supply of staked ETH.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The exact reason for this is explained in this Ethereum Foundation blog post (opens in a new tab).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Since finality requires a two-thirds majority, an attacker could prevent the network from reaching finality by voting with one-third of the total stake.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] There is a mechanism to defend against this: the inactivity leak (opens in a new tab).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This activates whenever the chain fails to finalize for more than four epochs.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The inactivity leak bleeds away the staked ETH from validators voting against the majority, allowing the majority to regain a two-thirds majority and finalize the chain.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The validator is expected to maintain sufficient hardware and connectivity to participate in block validation and proposal.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] In return, the validator is paid in ETH (their staked balance increases).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] On the other hand, participating as a validator also opens new avenues for users to attack the network for personal gain or sabotage.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] To prevent this, validators miss out on ETH rewards if they fail to participate when called upon, and their existing stake can be destroyed if they behave dishonestly.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Two primary behaviors can be considered dishonest: proposing multiple blocks in a single slot (equivocating) and submitting contradictory attestations.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The amount of ETH slashed depends on how many validators are also being slashed at around the same time.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This is known as the "correlation penalty" (opens in a new tab), and it can be minor (~1% stake for a single validator slashed on their own) or can result in 100% of the validator's stake getting destroyed (mass slashing event).
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] It is imposed halfway through a forced exit period that begins with an immediate penalty (up to 1 ETH) on Day 1, the correlation penalty on Day 18, and finally, ejection from the network on Day 36.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] They receive minor attestation penalties every day because they are present on the network but not submitting votes.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] This all means a coordinated attack would be very costly for the attacker.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] When the network performs optimally and honestly, there is only ever one new block at the head of the chain, and all validators attest to it.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] However, it is possible for validators to have different views of the head of the chain due to network latency or because a block proposer has equivocated.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Therefore, consensus clients require an algorithm to decide which one to favor.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The algorithm used in proof-of-stake Ethereum is called LMD-GHOST (opens in a new tab), and it works by identifying the fork that has the greatest weight of attestations in its history.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The threat of a 51% attack (opens in a new tab) still exists on proof-of-stake as it does on proof-of-work, but it's even riskier for the attackers.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] An attacker would need 51% of the staked ETH.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] They could then use their own attestations to ensure their preferred fork was the one with the most accumulated attestations.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] The 'weight' of accumulated attestations is what consensus clients use to determine the correct chain, so this attacker would be able to make their fork the canonical one.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] However, a strength of proof-of-stake over proof-of-work is that the community has flexibility in mounting a counter-attack.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] For example, the honest validators could decide to keep building on the minority chain and ignore the attacker's fork while encouraging apps, exchanges, and pools to do the same.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] They could also decide to forcibly remove the attacker from the network and destroy their staked ETH.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] These are strong economic defenses against a 51% attack.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Overall, proof-of-stake, as it is implemented on Ethereum, has been demonstrated to be more economically secure than proof-of-work.
[src:proof-of-stake/consensus-mechanisms-pos] Ethereum originally used proof-of-work but switched to proof-of-stake in September 2022.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:proof-of-stake/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:proof-of-stake/ouroboros-protocol] Ouroboros was published as "the first provable secure PoS consensus protocol".
[src:proof-of-stake/ouroboros-protocol] It was postulated by an academic team led by Aggelos Kiayias at the Annual International Cryptology Conference in 2017.
[src:proof-of-stake/ouroboros-protocol] Later that year, Ouroboros (Classic) was implemented by IOHK as the basis of the Cardano blockchain platform and various upgrades.
[src:proof-of-stake/ouroboros-protocol] Cardano's founder Charles Hoskinson has described the Ouroboros consensus mechanism as energy efficient.
[src:proof-of-stake/ouroboros-protocol] Nguyen et al. compared Ouroboros to other PoS protocols.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] Peercoin is based on an August 2012 paper that listed the authors as Scott Nadal and Sunny King.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] King, who also created Primecoin, is a pseudonym.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] The Peercoin source code is distributed under the MIT/X11 software license.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] Peercoin uses both the proof-of-work and proof-of-stake algorithms.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] Both are used to spread the distribution of new coins.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] During its primary years, Peercoin relied heavily on PoW, although there has now been a transition to PoS.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] Proof-of-stake is used to secure the network: The chain with longest PoS coin age wins in case of a blockchain split-up.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] To target a global 1% annual inflation rate, individual stakes typically receive a 3 - 5% annual reward, as only a minority of coins are actively staked.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] This reward is based on a dynamic portion (75% of the reward) and a static portion (25% of the reward).
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] The dynamic portion of the reward for an individual stake is based on the number of coins, their unspent age, and degree of global staking participation.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] Stake-for-Stake, periods of low (high) global staking participation will result in a higher (lower) dynamic reward.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] The static portion of the reward is based on the fraction of the existing total coin supply minted on average in a year, and is awarded regardless of stake size.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] As of December 2024, the static reward for a proof-of-stake block is approximately 1.4 PPC.
[src:proof-of-stake/peercoin] A transaction fee prevents spam and is burned (instead of being collected by a miner), benefiting the overall network.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] For a blockchain transaction to be recognized, it must be appended to the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] In a proof-of-stake blockchain, the appending entities are named *minters* or **validators** (in proof-of-work blockchains, this task is carried out by the miners); in most protocols, the validators receive a reward for doing so.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] For the blockchain to remain secure, it must have a mechanism to prevent a malicious user or group from taking over a majority of validation.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] PoS accomplishes this by requiring that validators have some quantity of blockchain tokens, requiring potential attackers to acquire a large fraction of the tokens on the blockchain to mount an attack.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Proof-of-work (PoW), another commonly used consensus mechanism, uses a validation of computational prowess to verify transactions, requiring a potential attacker to acquire a large fraction of the computational power of the validator network.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] This incentivizes consuming huge quantities of energy.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Riposo and Gupta showed that a formal PoS mathematical model can derive a metric for the expected gain of a staker.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] They introduced a forward-method model that computes staking rewards as the staking return per block-validation period and proved that the resulting interest equals the ratio of the average staking gain to the total staked coins.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The model incorporates PoS-specific factors such as slashing (penalties for misbehavior) and Maximal Extractable Value (MEV), showing that slashing reduces expected rewards and that MEV links transaction-fee extraction to the average staking gain.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] In addition, the authors illustrated the model using Ethereum 2.0, and presented an analogous derivation for PoW consensus.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Early PoS implementations were plagued by a number of new attacks that exploited the unique vulnerabilities of the PoS protocols.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Eventually, two dominant designs emerged: *Byzantine-fault-tolerance-based* and *chain-based* approaches.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The additional vulnerabilities of PoS schemes are directly related to their advantage: a relatively low amount of calculations required when constructing a blockchain.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The low amount of computing power involved allows a class of attacks that replace a non-negligible portion of the main blockchain with a hijacked version.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] These attacks are called in literature by different names, including *Long-Range*, *Alternative History*, *Alternate History*, and *History Revision*, and are unfeasible in the PoW schemes due to the sheer volume of calculations required.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The early stages of a blockchain are much more malleable for rewriting, as they likely have much smaller group of stakeholders involved, simplifying the collusion.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] If the per-block and per-transaction rewards are offered, then the malicious group can, for example, redo the entire history and collect these rewards.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The classic "Short-Range" attack (bribery attack) that rewrites just a small tail portion of the chain is also possible.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The PoS schemes enable low-cost creation of blockchain alternatives starting at any point in history (*costless simulation*); submitting these forks to eager validators endangers the stability of the system.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] If this situation persists, it can allow double-spending, where a digital token can be spent more than once.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] This can be mitigated through penalizing validators who validate conflicting chains ("economic finality") or by structuring the rewards so that there is no economic incentive to create conflicts.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Byzantine-fault-tolerance-based PoS are generally considered robust against this threat (see below).
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The smaller amount of calculations required for solving the puzzle for high-value stakeholders helps to avoid excessive hardware.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Also known as "committee-based", this scheme involves an election of a committee of validators using a verifiable random function with probabilities of being elected higher with higher stake.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Validators then randomly take turns producing blocks.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] NPoS is utilized by Ouroboros Praos and BABE.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The BFT consensus is used to finalize the most-voted block.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The scheme works as long as no more than a third of validators are dishonest.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] BFT schemes are used in Tendermint and Casper FFG.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Proof of stake delegated systems use a two-stage process: first, the stakeholders elect a validation committee, a.k.a.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] *witnesses*, by voting proportionally to their stakes, then the witnesses take turns in a round-robin fashion to propose new blocks that are then voted upon by the witnesses, usually in the BFT-like fashion.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Since there are fewer validators in the DPoS than in many other PoS schemes, the consensus can be established faster.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The scheme is used in many chains, including EOS, Lisk, Tron.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] In the liquid PoS anyone with a stake can declare themselves a validator, but for the small holders it makes sense to delegate their voting rights instead to larger players in exchange for some benefits (like periodic payouts).
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] A market is established where the validators compete on the fees, reputation, and other factors.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Token holders are free to switch their support to another validator at any time.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The exact definition of "stake" varies from implementation to implementation.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] For instance, some cryptocurrencies use the concept of "coin age", the product of the number of tokens with the amount of time that a single user has held them, rather than merely the number of tokens, to define a validator's stake.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The first functioning implementation of a proof-of-stake cryptocurrency was Peercoin, introduced in 2012.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Other cryptocurrencies, such as Blackcoin, Nxt, Cardano, and Algorand followed.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] However, as of 2017, PoS cryptocurrencies were still not as widely used as proof-of-work cryptocurrencies.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] In September 2022, Ethereum, the second-largest cryptocurrency, switched from PoW to a PoS consensus mechanism, after several proposals and some delays.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] US regulators have argued over the legal status of the proof-of-stake model, with the Securities and Exchange Commission claiming that staking rewards are the equivalent of interest, so coins such as ether and ada are financial securities.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] However, in 2024, the SEC sidestepped the question by recognising Ethereum market funds on condition that they did not stake their coins.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] The level of staking of ether at 27% of total supply was low compared with Cardano (66%) and Solana (63%).
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] However, not staking their tokens meant that the funds were losing about 3% of potential returns a year.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] In January 2022, Erik Thedéen, the vice-chair of the European Securities and Markets Authority, called on the EU to ban the PoW model in favor of PoS because of the latter's lower energy consumption.
[src:proof-of-stake/proof-of-stake] Ethereum's switch to proof-of-stake was estimated to have cut its energy use by over 99%.
